The Benefit is what your target consumer gets out of using your product or service. 
 <br><br>
We have noticed that clients have an overwhelming fascination with the Brand Name. They think their success hinges upon it… Nothing could be further from the truth. The most important communication element of your selling proposition is a combination of two elements that morph into one. The first of those elements is the BENEFIT. The reason for its importance is in its relevance to your target consumer. It is not about your product of service… it's about your target consumer. 
 <br><br>
A benefit is typically a "Why-to-Buy" or sometimes a "Call-to-Action." A why-to-buy is simply a claim that answers the question, "Why should I buy this product?" A call-to-action is a statement that encourages a direct action that results in the sale of the product. 
 <br><br>
I will demonstrate. Let's assume you are marketing Benadryl allergy medicine. Here are two possible benefits, one a why-to-buy and the other a call-to-action. The why-to-buy: "Relieves Symptoms Now." That is straight to the point and appears to be very powerful on the surface. Looking closer you may observe that it is a general statement relative to the product. Still it seems perfectly appropriate as is. 
 <br><br>
Now consider a one-word change that will give it a whole new meaning: "Relieve Your Symptoms Now." Notice two distinct characteristics that are present here, but were missing before? The statement is now about the consumer instead of the product. Second, it suggests that the target consumer needs to do something now in order to benefit from using the product. As long as the consumer considers the statement appropriate, the more personal call-to-action will score well above the why-to-buy. That's all it may take to make it be perceived as remarkable. 
 <br><br>
A great example of a why-to-buy benefit is demonstrated below under the brand name of Central Pharmacy. Apparently, its owners wisely realized that their brand name "Central" (look closely) was relatively unimportant and subordinated it to their Generic Descriptor "Pharmacy." After all people driving by will look for a pharmacy not a "central." They wisely dropped their benefit "The Healthy Body Shop" right under where it will experience high visibility. Very unusual and very smart positioning. Who wouldn't want a healthy body?

