Overall the most powerful benefits are those that define what the consumer gets out of using the product. Therefore by definition they are not product specific. 
<br><br> 
The lesson here is that the higher you climb up the ladder, the more personal the benefit becomes. The more personal, the more attractive to the target consumer, and therefore, the more powerful. Note that in this conversation, we only barely distinguish the difference between a human and a product. When you get personal, the line between patronizing and authenticity becomes very fine. Target consumers will always interpret appearing authentic as appropriate, but even a slight hint of being patronized and they will completely reject your selling proposition as inauthentic. Better safe than sorry on this one. If you think you're getting personal, research it formally or by asking potential consumers. Be sure to check it out because the penalty for going over the line is mass rejection.
 <br><br> 
